<br>
The flames of Hate danced both in his blue eyes and the red fire that limned the sigil on his left arm.  Without even a greeting to the other warriors of Hate, he stalked into his chambers.  He was angered briefly at what he found there.<br>
<br>
All his incense was burning.  His meditation items arranged just so.  It wasn’t that anything wasn’t the way he preferred it.  It was merely the fact that he knew one or more of the servants or slaves were taking care of his needs against his wishes.  Perhaps his anger was more geared towards the fact that tonight, of all nights, he was almost happy that he had little else to prepare for his meditation.  The matter was of little consequence, and pushed out of Vresk’s mind entirely.<br>
<br>
Quickly he disrobed, putting everything in its proper place.  Then, going to the steaming stream at the back of the chamber (kept warm by the lava tube running close to the surface here, the same lava tube that made his chamber uncomfortable for the Teir’Dal), he cleansed himself both physically and spiritually.  A few dried scales fell off, but all in all, he hardly looked like he’d been in intense battle.<br>
<br>
Having cleansed himself, he concentrated on finding his center before stepping carefully into the middle of the chamber and slipping into deep meditation.  Immediate chaos ensued.  A devastated landscape full of rotting corpses and flowing blood filled his senses.  A million souls cried out a single word.  A single name.  Mistmoore.<br>
<br>
The monk quickly centered himself again before being overwhelmed by the vision.  His vision blurred and shifted.  When it again became clear, he found himself facing a shadow figure.  Its entire body from head to toe was composed of blackest pitch.  In the background stood an enormous dragon which Vresk immediately recognized as the Dragon of Hate.<br>
<br>
Vresk studied the figure in more detail.  It was humanoid in shape, a bit short for a full blooded human though.  Perhaps some sort of elf.  He couldn’t make out any details of the face at all.  *Dark tidings, Faceless One* he projected mentally to the figure.<br>
<br>
The figure moved, appearing to center its attention on the monk.  *So you have come at last*<br>
<br>
*Aye* the Iksar was wary, untrusting of this situation.  Normally he controlled his own visions during his meditations, but he sensed now that he wasn’t completely the master here.<br>
<br>
*You have reached the status of Master of your people, Vresk.  MY people.  The people I created*<br>
<br>
*My journey has come far.  I have further yet to go*<br>
<br>
The figure chuckled darkly.  The sound reminded him of the lizardman throwbacks in the Temple of Cazic Thule.  *So you come from victory in the battles and return a humble monk?*<br>
<br>
*I simply am what I am, nothing more.  And the Harvest gained no victory this day.  Though Faeolin stands defeated in combat, it is Mythral that yet rises and continues his schemes.*<br>
<br>
*Your words are wise.  Your voice calm.  You hide your fear well, Iksar*<br>
<br>
In his mind, Vresk’s “voice” grew hard.  *There is no fear in me*<br>
<br>
*Oh?*  The figure seemed amused.  *Then what am I then?*<br>
<br>
*A fragment of the Faceless One’s Will, bound to the sigil he trapped within me.  I am here to remove you.  You are no longer welcome.*<br>
<br>
The laughter changed abruptly, and the figure grew larger, more menacing.  *You _dare_ threaten me?*<br>
<br>
*I threaten nobody.  I state a simple fact.  I am the Master here, not you.*<br>
<br>
*I have more control here than you can imagine.*  The figure gestured, and the landscape changed abruptly.  They were overlooking Cabilis.  Or rather the ruins of Cabilis.  Buildings and pillars had collapsed in on themselves, and fires burned in over half the city.  Bodies were everywhere.  Burned, twisted, gutted.  And in one corner, preparing the final defense, a full legion of Iksar; warriors, shadowknights, monks, shamans, necromancers, all the remaining force of the Empire gathered.<br>
<br>
Outside the city was the source of the conflict.  Hundreds of Teir’Dal surrounded the city.  Engines of war were rolled into place, and another volley of flaming material was sent crashing into the ruined city.<br>
<br>
The last remaining legion marched out of battle, and the Teir’Dal army prepared.  They were tense, waiting for something.  All eyes were at the head of the dark elf columns, awaiting a signal.  A single Iksar stood at the head of the amassed army.  An armor clad figure approached the Iksar.  The monk could tell by the insignia on the figure’s insignia that it was the Thresher of the Harvest.  “What are you orders?”<br>
<br>
“Kill them.  ALL of them,” the voice was Vresk’s own.  “Let no Iksar survive the Violent Harvest.”<br>
<br>
And the battle was joined.  The details of the battle mattered not.  The end results did.  Of the mighty empire of the Iksar, not a single survivor remained.  Vresk’s final act was to survey the carnage before ending his own life.<br>
<br>
*This is what you head for.  Traitor to your own people.  You fear this.  I sense it.*<br>
<br>
*You know me not then.  While this is one possibility, it is certainly not the only one.  While I find the possibility of warring with my people regrettable, I will not allow them to continue to stagnate under your current rule.  They will be delivered, or they will perish by my hand.*<br>
<br>
The image of carnage wavered and fell, leaving him alone once again with the dark figure.  Vresk could see that it had faded somewhat.  Some of the background could be seen through its transparent darkness.  *Very well,* the figure projected in his mind.  *You may win this time, but do not think it will always be so.  I will be here lurking, ready to bring you back to where you belong when you grow weak.*<br>
<br>
*You are no longer welcome here*<br>
<br>
*It wasn’t a question, Whiff*<br>
<br>
Vresk felt his Hate gather.  He formed it in his mind into a ball of energy.  A sphere of his pure rage.  The roiling black mass pulsed and writhed.  Vresk hurled it with all his strength at the figure.  There was a tremendous explosion that rocked him back on his tail.  When the smoke cleared, the figure had vanished.<br>
<br>
Vresk came out of his reverie relaxed and somehow feeling cleansed.  He stood in his chambers and looked around.  Stretching his muscles, he exited his chamber, prepared for the coming battles.<br>
